															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-freeze" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(604027); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=604027&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610205698" alt="Dr Freeze" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=604027)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-freeze" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(604027); return false;" >Dr Freeze</a></span> <span class="odate time_1469703408 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">28 Jul 2016 10:56</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2545083">
									

<p>Solved the guard/item arrangement after a while (albeit perhaps with some lucky guesses when I tried just starting to put down possibilities and see how they worked out - it doesn't seem like there's any chain of logic you can use to deduce positions one step at a time, besides the freebie of Subong's position), but couldn't figure out where the hell to go for the extraction - there seemed to be a million possible directions to go with nothing to distinguish them. After finally giving in and looking at the discussion for clues, your hint here was enough for me to figure it out, and then it all makes sense; a very clever puzzle like all the rest, and this is an amazing SCP. But I felt the extraction had too few clues and too many misleading red herrings within the puzzle itself.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>Particularly, the mention of &quot;two a.m.&quot; made it seem like the rocket launcher was somehow associated with the number 2; and the mention of Class D's becoming E's is an entirely separate clue following an entirely separate logic from the name-letter-object association hinted at by the rest of the notes, but its proximity to the &quot;letter grade&quot; discussion made it seem misleadingly like they were all hints to the same rule. Also, it would have been less ambiguous if they'd discussed giving different letters for the rocket launcher or Scranton rather than the alarm (they'd have needed different names, but that'd be easy enough to change), because, since there are two alarms, it makes it sound like one corresponds to a C (logically, the one held by a researcher, since Ricardo is also given the title of researcher) while the other one corresponds to an A; but, if they'd been discussing giving different letters to one of the objects of which there was only one copy in the puzzle, it would have been easier to dismiss that possibility and deduce that the items correspond to a common rule that produces different letters based on the holder.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Of course, there's nothing wrong with making a puzzle difficult, and including red herrings is certainly within your rights; but I think a puzzle is more fair and satisfying when there aren't many alternative trains of reasoning that seem just as valid as the correct path from the available evidence, but that only end in dead ends. And I didn't get the impression that these were intentional traps, so much as minor choices of phrasing and formatting that you didn't realize would be as misleading as they are.</p>
<p>Once again, though, great work creating this SCP! There doesn't seem to be anything else like it on the site, and I doubt there ever will be.</p>

							</div>

								
					
